text: Just from this trailer, I'm disappointed that it's depicting Native American Peoples' lore (whether real mythology or fictional) as being evil. Sure, many peoples did have negative spirits, but there was always a reason and they served a purpose. The implication that the stone he's holding is a totem said to be important to a spirit keeper, or spiritual guardian, that is really just some "spooky murderous ghost thing that's evil because what else would it be?" is insulting and a dead horse. Every peoples, native to the Americas or not, have an item that represents an aspect into the realm of death, and I'm tired that it's always jump-scare, gonna get'cha dead, "oh, look you all died, the next guy to investigate is gonna get it now!". Can we get more about "Oh shit! it's pissed, let's fix this!"?

text: Strange that a _guardian_ of the spirit world--presumably an entity that protect the living from the shades of the dead--would be such a malevolent presence; scaring the shit out of everyone and maybe trying to kill people instead of getting them to _take the stone back where he found it._ That sounds like a much better movie. Boy accidentally steals one of five guardians to the spirit world, allowing a few shades to escape. True to its purpose, the guardian tries to _protect_ the family as best it can on its own, recognizing there was no ill intent to begin with, and must somehow communicate that they must return the stone to dispel the evils now haunting them. That's probably not as safe a bet as "evil non christian ghost thingy possesses child and terrorizes all american family." And we all know investors like safe bets.
